title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory M1 Garand .30-06 1944/45
postcontent:
Springfield Armory M1 Garand .30-06, serial number 3509-xxx. Manufactured Dec 1944 – March 1945. Barrel is also Springfield (Feb 45), as are most marked components. No import marks.

This Garand is in very good used condition. We test fired it and it shoots fine, it cycled through a full 8 round clip and ejected the clip at the end.

Part Details:

-Receiver: marked “D 28291 35” on leg, various other markings. Excellent condition, absolutely no pitting. Has dark parkerized finish that shows some wear.

-Barrel: marked ”1 SA 2 45” in op rod slot, with various other markings. Top of barrel (not normally visible) is marked “D35448-34-Y-212-B- -1”. Same dark parkerized finish as the receiver, nice appearance. Four groove rifling, bore is a little frosty but not dark, crown good. ME: 3 1/2, TE: 3.

-Op rod: Springfield, marked “D35392 SA”. Dark parkerized finish very similar to barrel and receiver. Finish shows some wear. No rust, very good condition.

-Op rod catch: late SA type, unmarked, parkerized

-Bullet guide: milled WWII type, parkerized, hammer forge mark “S 61” visible

-Follower: SA type, marked “12”, parkerized

-Follower arm: late type, no bevel, unmarked, parkerized

-Follower rod: long fork, riveted, unmarked, parkerized

-Clip release: round front type, unmarked, parkerized

-Bolt: HRA, marked “65287 HRA .U.”, with hole in underside, parkerized

-Firing pin: half round, no chrome tip, unmarked

-Elevation knob: postwar, marked “NHC” (New Haven Clock), parkerized

-Windage knob: postwar, marked “DRC”, parkerized

-Rear sight base: unmarked, parkerized

-Rear sight cover: SA type, with narrow ribs, parkerized, has minor dents

-Rear sight aperture: unmarked, parkerized, double track

-Trigger housing: Springfield, marked “D28290-12-SA”, small pad, cloverleaf hole, parkerized, no pitting, very good condition

-Trigger guard: SA milled type, unmarked, parkerized

-Trigger: no extra hole, parkerized, drop forge mark “15” is visible

-Hammer: Springfield, marked “C46008-5 SA”, parkerized

-Hammer spring housing: parkerized

-Hammer spring plunger: WWII Springfield type with wings, parkerized

-Safety: Springfield, round top with hole, marked “SA 11”, parkerized

-Gas cylinder: wide sight platform, flat on top of rear ring, unmarked. Very good working condition, finish is worn

-Front sight: 0.65 wide, unmarked, no seal.

-Gas cylinder lock: beveled front WWII type. Finish is worn off.

-Gas cylinder lock screw: postwar cross slot, grenade launcher valve type, marked “C” and “I”. Finish is worn off.

-Stock: Appears to be GI walnut, no cracks, some dings and gouges but none severe. Marked with stars and eagle on left side, circled “P” inside pistol grip.

-Handguards: unmarked, walnut, rear guard has slide clearance cut. Both guards have some dings and gouges. Front guard has a couple of grain cracks, don’t appear to be going anywhere but this is the easy one to remove for repair or replacement.

-Lower band: WWII (1943-EOP) type, with “O”, flat top

-Buttplate: shows some wear, appears the same age as the stock

title: For Sale:  Steyr USR AUG 5.56 223
postcontent: Steyr USR/AUG 5.56 .223 Pre-Ban. This rifle in excellent condition overall and has only some minor handling marks from being bumped in the safe. It has seen very little use as evidenced by it's ejection port that has little to no wear. The rifle is based on the famed AUG A2 platform with a few key modifications that allowed it to slip in under Clinton's assault weapons ban. These rifle are rare and unique with only 3000 ever imported into the US. They possess all of the great attributes of the AUG A2 plus a heavy match grade 20" barrel making this the most accurate AUG ever made. This particular rifle has been modified with the quick change barrel button seen on A1's A2's and A3's. To be clear, This is the genuine factory Steyr 20" heavy barrel that came with the weapon. The only modification to this rifle was the addition of the barrel change button. It originally came with a lock screw to get the rifle in under the 1994 assault weapons ban so that owners couldn't do quick barrel changes to barrels with flash suppressors.The scope is also the genuine SWAROVSKI that came mounted on the rifle and has never been off. The rifle comes in a nice black case with it's factory scope adjustment tool, sling, factory accessory rail to mount iron sights or non-factory optics, two (2) thirty (30) round magazines, and it's manual. Cash Only

Burris 3-9x40mm Fullfield II Rifle Scope w/ Burris 10x32mm Landmark Binoculars gives you a full spot-and-shoot package! This value package from Burris includes the Burris 3x-9x 40mm Fullfield-II Riflescope and the Burris Landmark 10x32mm Binoculars.

The Burris Fullfield II Rifle Scope has a one-piece main tube and eyepiece, Burris envied steel-on-steel adjustment system, and HiLume multi-coatings on every single air to glass lens surface. The Burris FullField-II Scope is even more forgiving for eye position, is a little shorter, and a good bit lighter. The magnification ring and eyepiece have been made into one solid unit requiring only two seals rather than three. To change magnification, simply turn the entire eyepiece. Burris Fullfield 2 Scope eliminated most of the potential leak paths in the eyepiece/power ring area and sealed the remainder with special quad seals instead of O-rings. The adjustment system has been moved to improve mounting options and the European-style adjustable eyepiece requires no locking mechanism. The Ballistic Plex reticle has a lower vertical crosshair with small ballistic lines that automatically compensate for bullet drop from 100 to 500 yards for many common cartridges. The Burris Fullfield-2 Riflescope is lighter, better sealed, and has a relocated adjustment system compared to the original Burris Fullfield.

The Burris Landmark Binoculars combine light weight, fully coated lenses and water resistant, fogproof construction. These Burris Binoculars also include a tough rubber armor coating and twist-up eyecups. Top all this off with a neck strap, carrying case, a full year warranty and a very affordable price and you have yourself a synonym for optical value.

The extremely hot water transfers its heat to the scope and the internal nitrogen expends 100% testing assures quality. Each scope is filled and purged at least 24 times with high quality, laboratory grade dry nitrogen. Each nitrogen cycle absorbs airborne and residual surface moisture that is evacuated from the scope. Burris uses specially made quad seals to provide double insurance against leakage.
Fog proof: The nitrogen contained in the scope is of high quality (ultra dry, laboratory grade nitrogen), ultra pure and ultra clean. To be sure that all airborne moisture and surfaces moisture within a scope is evacuated, testing consists of 24 cycles of pressurizing the scope and then subjecting it to a vacuum. The tests are both cost & time intensive.
Shock proof: Burris scopes are subjected to extreme recoil tests. An impact machine is used to measure and duplicate the recoil pulse acceleration and duration. This machine has been calibrated and verified by an independent laboratory to replicate the wave frequencies and shock impulses that a scope is subjected to.
Ballistic Plex reticle - with a basic crosshair reticle, calculating hold-over is a mix of art, science and just plain luck, which is why Burris developed the Ballistic Plex reticle. The key is the copyrighted lower vertical crosshair. With most common hunting cartridges, a shooter can use the reticle to compensate for bullet drop and aim dead-on at targets from 100 to 500 yards out. The need for hold-over guesstimation is eliminated. Using it is simple. Start by sighting-in your rifle at 100 or 200 yards at your scope's highest magnification.
